    <div class="row orange section-p content">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h6>Topic A<br/>THE SITUATION IN UKRAINE</h6>
            <p>Ukraine, part of the former USSR, is a country in eastern Europe that finds itself in a strategic position between Europe and Russia (Stratfor, 2014). Located in the north shore of the Black Sea, the Ukrainian territory is a major transit hub for Pan-European Corridors and for Russian pipelines that supply Europe with oil and gas, a fact that gives the country great geopolitical importance in the region (Ahmed, 2014).</p>
            <p>Today’s situation in Ukraine involves conflicts between the central government in Kiev and separatist groups, mainly from Donetsk and Lugansk, which are connected to the country’s clashes with the Russian Federation. The current crisis can be traced back to the end of 2013, when the government of Viktor Yanukovitch refused to sign a framework agreement with the European Union and accepted financial help from Russia. As a result, several popular riots broke out, protesting what they perceived as an abdication of Ukraine’s future entry into the European Union. Tensions escalated and the country came to the edge of a civil war when Yanukovitch was ousted and replaced by Petro Poroshenko, a pro-Europe politician. Further clashes opposed those in favor of Poroshenko and the alliance with EU and those in favor of Yanukovich and the connections with Russia.</p>
            <p>Under this context, the Crimean region declared itself, through a referendum, as part of the Russian Federation. This decision was supported by Moscow, since maintaining influence in its surrounding regions was considered vital to the national security and since Sebastopol, a Russian base located in Crimea, is essential for Russia’s trade and military projection in the Black Sea (Colin, 2007). The annexation of this territory, opposed by Ukraine, the USA and the European Union, created a chasm between these countries and Russia.</p>
            <p>In march, 2014, Ukraine signed an Association Agreement with the European Union and shortly after NATO suspended its cooperation with the Russian Federation. Pro-Russian protesters then took control of the eastern Ukraine provinces of Donetsk and Lugansk, which declared their independence and faced severe repression from the Kiev government. The new republics receive veiled support from Russia in the fight against the central Ukrainian government, which, by its turn, is assisted by Western countries (Mearsheimer, 2014).</p>
            <p>A cease-fire was declared in September, but the armed conflict continued and tensions escalated in Mariupol, near Crimea, due to a possible Russian desire to open a land route to Crimea through Ukraine’s southeast (Stratfor, 2015). A new cease-fire was signed in the beginning of 2015, but its future is unclear as the crisis involves the diverging interests of the European powers, NATO and Russia. </p>
            <p>Since the beginning of 2014, several sanctions, such as arms embargoes, cutoffs of gas supplies and prohibitions of trade, were unilaterally imposed on Ukraine and Crimea.  What initially was a disturbance in Ukrainian politics became a large-scale crisis, opposing Russian, European and NATO military forces in demonstrations of strength and support for their respective allies that further aggravate the situation. It is up to the UN Security Council to decide how the conflict can be solved through political means, before a new armed conflict of huge proportions once more erupts in European territory.</p>

