        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h6>Topic B<br/>THE SITUATION IN YEMEN</h6>
            <p>Located in a strategic position in the oil-rich Gulf of Aden, Yemen is one of the poorest and least developed countries of the world. The port of Aden gives access to the Bab el-Mandeb strait - situated between the Arabian Peninsula and the Horn of Africa-, which is the entrance for the Red Sea and its connection to the Indian Ocean (P. F. Visentini 2012, Balanche 2014). </p>
            <p>This country of Sunni majority was divided between South and North Yemen until 1990, when a unification process took place. Yet, a separatist motivation existed in the country since 1994, when the South lost a civil war against government forces (Balanche 2014, Zimmerman 2014, P. F. Visentini 2012). Alongside with southern separatism, Yemen also had to cope with two other serious issues: a Northern Shiite insurgency, the Houthis, that started rebelling against the government in 2003; and al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP), the powerful Yemeni al-Qaeda’s branch (Mudallali 2015, Ratnam and Naylor 2015, Zimmerman 2014). </p>
            <p>A crisis erupted when the Houthi rebels took over the capital, Sana’a, and the cities of Saada and Hodeïda, and later kidnapped the president’s chief of state and seized the presidential palace. Elected in 2012, after a series of protests collapsed the former President’s regime, Abdu Rabbu Mansour Hadi cooperated very closely with the United States in order to contain the terrorist activities of the Yemeni Al-Qaeda’s affiliate, which led the country to be considered the perfect example of terrorism fight by Obama’s administration (P. G. Visentini 2014, Boot 2015, Rosen 2015). After his deposition, UNSC issued a statement recognizing Hadi as the legitimate president of Yemen, and urging that the parties solved the problem with dialoge. Nevertheless, this had almost no effects, and it did not take long before Hadi resigned and went to Aden, in the south (J.H.-R. 2014, Les Echos 2015).</p>
            <p>The resignation of the president was a shift in the balance of power in favor of the Houthis, but also a very fortunate scenario for the rise of AQAP and ISIS branches. A South secession is also a possibility, since the quasi-autonomous southern tribes are joining forces with Hadi's loyal forces to fight the shiite faction trying to rule the country. Saudi Arabia, a country that has always financed the Yemeni government, may withdraw its help if the Houthis continue to keep power on their hands, which might lead the state to collapse. The Saudis and the Yemeni media believe that the Iranian government has always helped the Northern Shiite insurrection, which may be a new reason to increase tension between Riyadh and Tehran. The latest, however, denied involvement with the Houthis when these accusations started in 2003, after the Houthis first declared war against Saleh. </p>
            <p>The United States are also extremely concerned, since without Hadi, they may have lost a potential ally on their fight against terrorism (Henderson 2015, Ratnam and Naylor 2015, Guéhenno 2015).  This issue led United States to withdraw all their remaining forces in the country, allowing AQAP and ISIS increase even more its presence and activities.</p>
            <p>Therefore, it is of great urgency that the United Nations Security Council meet again to discuss the situation in Yemen, for its unstable political situation may strongly affect the dynamics of Middle Eastern and global politics. It is extremely necessary that the countries discuss if it is possible that the Houthis become allies on the fight against terrorism, and what could be the effects in the case that the southern secession movement succeed. Both the growth of AQAP’s activities and the continuity of USA’s drone strikes on al-Qaeda targets must be a concern for the international community, as may also the devastating and worsening socioeconomic conditions of Yemeni population in such a crisis. In a context where Sunni ISIS forces keep getting strength in neighboring countries and now inside Yemen, is it possible that a common enemy like al-Qaeda can reunite longstanding opponents, as Iran and Saudi Arabia or even the United States? How will all these changes and competitions affect the international relations of the Middle East and the International System? </p>
